WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.240 --> 00:00:12.420
[Music] Good day everyone. I'm Norman Walberger,&nbsp;
and we're investigating a new approach to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:19.920
arithmetic based on multi-sets—data structures&nbsp;
which are unordered and allow repetition. Today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:25.200
we're going to take the big step from poly numbers&nbsp;
to multi numbers. Let me quickly review what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:32.760
did in our previous video. We introduced zero as&nbsp;
the multi-set, or more shortly, mset, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.760 --> 00:00:38.700
empty and has nothing in it. We introduced the&nbsp;
type of natural number. The natural number is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:43.620
an mset of zeros. So there's a natural number&nbsp;
that's actually probably the simplest natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.620 --> 00:00:51.900
number which is not zero itself, and it's called&nbsp;
one. This natural number has two zeros in it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:58.200
It's got the usual name of two. This is&nbsp;
three, etc. So this is the usual natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:05.340
number story. A poly number is an mset of natural&nbsp;
numbers, and the simplest one is this one, alpha,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.340 --> 00:01:14.640
which is just the mset containing one. Here is a&nbsp;
more general poly number: 0, 0, 0, 1, 3, 4, 4. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:19.380
these are all natural numbers. This is an mset of&nbsp;
natural numbers, so therefore it's a poly number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:25.740
And then we also introduced multi numbers.&nbsp;
A multi number is an mset of poly numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:26.820 --> 00:01:34.260
So the simplest one there would be the mset&nbsp;
consisting just of alpha, and we haven't yet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:39.300
given it a name. That's going to be interesting&nbsp;
for us today—to investigate how we should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:45.660
get some terminology going for these&nbsp;
multi numbers. Here's a more general&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:49.620
kind of multi-number. So it's an mset&nbsp;
consisting of—there's a poly number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.620 --> 00:01:53.460
there's another poly number, there's another poly&nbsp;
number, and there's another poly number. So it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.060 --> 00:02:00.360
an mset of poly numbers. Repetitions are allowed&nbsp;
and it's unordered. There's no commas, and so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:08.280
this is a multi-number. Today, we want to really&nbsp;
talk about the big step going from here to here.

00:02:08.280 --> 00:02:15.540
It might be useful to introduce this designation&nbsp;
of a pure mset to denote one of these structures&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:22.080
that is obtained by starting with empty&nbsp;
msets and just putting them in other msets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:31.200
so just nesting empty msets inside other msets,&nbsp;
etc. So this is contained in this sort of ongoing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:36.000
sequence. Here we started with zero, which is a&nbsp;
type, and then we had Nat, which includes zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.400
and then poly, and multi, and clearly we could&nbsp;
keep on going in a kind of a step-by-step fashion.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.460
So I want to introduce this idea because it's&nbsp;
certainly possible that later on we might be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:53.880
interested in msets of other things—other kinds&nbsp;
of objects, not just empty msets and things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.880 --> 00:03:00.540
formed from them. Alright, so the advantage&nbsp;
of making this specific is that this way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:05.760
the operations that we're going to talk about&nbsp;
later are all sort of consistently defined on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:12.240
these things because an mset, in this context of&nbsp;
pure mset, is already an mset of msets, and it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:17.940
already an mset of msets of msets, etc. So I also&nbsp;
might want to point out that we should not think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:23.400
about these things as objects. So it's not as&nbsp;
if we have an object of all multi-sets, okay?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:28.560
We want to avoid that sort of modern set theory&nbsp;
approach where we think that we've got all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:34.740
multi-sets contained in here. No, no. What we're&nbsp;
doing is we're rather identifying a type, okay? So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.740 --> 00:03:40.140
you should think about it as being something like&nbsp;
instructions for a computer. So the computer gets&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:44.940
some input, and the computer is able to read&nbsp;
that input and then decide whether the object&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:50.040
is of this type or some other type, okay? That's&nbsp;
what we're talking about. These are not objects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:56.280
and I want to just emphasize that there's this&nbsp;
basic principle that runs through a lot of my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:02.280
exposition, which is that we want write-downable&nbsp;
mathematics. We want to separate or distance&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:07.440
ourselves from the 20th-century abstractions&nbsp;
which have allowed people to think about things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.860
which they are not actually able to write&nbsp;
down. So we don't want to be doing that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:17.040
okay? So we want to insist that all the pure&nbsp;
msets that we're talking about are completely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:23.280
unambiguously write-downable. You could actually&nbsp;
exhibit them in their entirety, not with any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:32.760
requirements of alternate universes or who knows&nbsp;
what, beyond our vision. So in particular, have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:37.860
look at these. These are examples of things which,&nbsp;
from our point of view at least at this stage,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:45.900
are not allowable. We are not allowed to say, "Oh,&nbsp;
consider this pure mset. What is this? Oh, it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.900 --> 00:04:51.060
what you get when you start with an empty mset&nbsp;
like a box, and then you put that inside a bigger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:55.920
box, and you put that inside a bigger box, and you&nbsp;
put that inside a bigger box, and you keep going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.700 --> 00:05:01.680
without stopping. Keep going. Everything&nbsp;
is contained in a bigger box to infinity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:08.160
whatever that means." Okay, that's the kind of&nbsp;
thing that 20th-century mathematicians were not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:15.060
reluctant to talk about. If you actually look&nbsp;
at the foundations of analysis or differential&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:20.640
geometry or algebraic geometry or topology,&nbsp;
it's essentially this kind of talking which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:26.220
is at the core of much of these subjects. Okay,&nbsp;
we do not want to go there, okay? So for us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.220 --> 00:05:31.500
this kind of object where you have to do an&nbsp;
infinite number of things is not going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:37.680
allowed. Similarly, if going the other way, we can&nbsp;
start with a box, and inside it put another box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:41.760
and inside that you put another box, inside&nbsp;
that you put another box, and then you keep&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:47.880
going again to infinity. Okay, we're not allowed&nbsp;
to use that language, okay? Because we can't write&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:53.040
the thing down completely. This is obviously not&nbsp;
an adequate representation just like this isn't.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.420 --> 00:06:00.900
So these are not the kinds of things that we want&nbsp;
to do. But I want to keep open the possibility&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:07.020
that there's an idea contained here, right? There&nbsp;
is some kind of idea, and it's possible for us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:14.640
perhaps access that idea in a completely&nbsp;
write-downable, finite, concrete fashion.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:19.680
But we would have to do that in a different way&nbsp;
from doing something like this with three dots,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:25.260
okay? So I'm not saying that this object will&nbsp;
never or these objects will never be part of our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.260 --> 00:06:31.680
world. I'm just saying that when we do eventually&nbsp;
want to try to think about something like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.680 --> 00:06:36.960
we're going to have to think about them in&nbsp;
different ways that allow us still to write them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:45.180
down completely finitely and write-downably, okay?&nbsp;
And it's also useful to point out that later on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:50.700
we may want to depart from our pure mset&nbsp;
point of view and consider other kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:55.680
data structures like in the LOM system: lists,&nbsp;
order sets, multi-sets, and sets. Right now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.680 --> 00:07:00.720
we're just focusing on multi-sets, but it will&nbsp;
become useful potentially for us to consider other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:07.020
such structures, okay? So in that case, we might&nbsp;
depart from this very pure mset point of view.

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:11.820
So our two basic operations are addition and&nbsp;
multiplication, and let's review them here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:11.820 --> 00:07:16.980
I hope you've watched Math Foundations 227, the&nbsp;
previous video, where we introduced this approach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:22.740
and it's fresh in your mind. So addition is the&nbsp;
simplest possible thing. We just take msets and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:28.560
we dump the contents out into another box. That's&nbsp;
addition of msets. Very simple. So for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:34.080
here's an mset, here's an mset, here's an mset.&nbsp;
This mset here has some poly numbers in them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:40.020
These are poly numbers, and this one here has some&nbsp;
poly numbers and also a number, but they're all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:48.360
msets of poly numbers, so these are all multi&nbsp;
numbers. And we just get the sum by dumping them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:56.220
out. So the 3, the 3, the 1, 2, the 0, the 0, the&nbsp;
1, the 3, the 4. Multiplication is one step up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:01.320
a little bit more sophisticated in that it&nbsp;
relies on the prior definition of addition.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:08.460
But we're going to be adding elements of the&nbsp;
various things to be multiplied in all possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:13.740
ways. So to multiply these three msets, we&nbsp;
take one element from this one, one element&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:20.400
from this one, and one element from this one,&nbsp;
and we add them. And because addition doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:26.940
depend on the order in which we do things, so&nbsp;
also multiplication is not going to depend on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:32.340
order, so we don't need to worry about bracketing.&nbsp;
In other words, a big simplification. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:38.880
so what do we actually get here? So we've got,&nbsp;
this mset has mset 2 and 3. It has mset 4, mset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:45.120
4 in it. This one has mset 1, 6, and a 0. So we're&nbsp;
multiplying them. So we have to take elements from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:50.880
each one. So let's take this mset 2, this mset&nbsp;
4, this mset 1, 6, and we're going to add them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.780 --> 00:08:58.620
This one, mset 2, mset 4, and the 0, and we'll&nbsp;
add them. Then mset 2 and then this mset 4 and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:04.200
this mset 1, 6, add them. This mset 2, this mset&nbsp;
4, and then 0 and add them. And then the same kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:08.580
of thing, but now we take this number 3, the&nbsp;
number 3 plus the mset 4 plus the mset 1, 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:17.760
and add them. The mset 3, this mset 4, the 0, and&nbsp;
add them. This mset 3, this mset 4, this mset 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:25.380
6, and add them. This mset 3, this mset 4, and&nbsp;
this 0, and we add them. Okay, when we actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:31.440
do that, okay, the sum of these things, just dump&nbsp;
them out, we get a 2, a 4, a 1, and a 6. Here we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:37.380
get a 2, a 4. We add 0. Zero, remember, is the&nbsp;
empty mset. Adding that doesn't do anything,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:37.380 --> 00:09:45.120
so you just get 2, 4. This one here, you get&nbsp;
2, 4, 1, 6. The same thing as over here. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:55.500
the natural number 3 as an mset is 0, 0, 0. It&nbsp;
consists of three zeros. Okay, so when we look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.500 --> 00:10:04.140
at it that way, then adding them comes up with&nbsp;
0, 0, 0, 4, 1, 6. Here, the sum is 0, 0, 0, 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:08.940
and this adding zero doesn't do anything,&nbsp;
and you're just adding an empty mset.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:13.440
And here we get the same thing as here, and here&nbsp;
we get the same thing as here. So this is how we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:21.480
calculate the product of msets. One of&nbsp;
the interesting aspects of this approach&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:28.320
to arithmetic is that it seems that no matter how&nbsp;
far you go, it's just part of some bigger picture.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:35.760
Okay, so that means that we never have this&nbsp;
feeling of a complete understanding. We feel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.740
that our understanding is always just temporary&nbsp;
and waiting for the next level, the next step,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:45.840
the bigger picture of which this is just some&nbsp;
part. So we have to be a little bit modest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:52.800
but it also means that we need to be flexible&nbsp;
about the terminology and our notation and our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:58.440
thinking because it might be possible that with&nbsp;
a few steps up, we start to see what we've just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.440 --> 00:11:04.200
previously been doing in a new light, and we have&nbsp;
to maybe improve our notation to make it fit with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:10.020
this bigger picture. So that's going to happen&nbsp;
right here as we try to move from poly to multi.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:19.620
So we've introduced this notation, alpha, which&nbsp;
corresponds with my usual terminology for poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:24.240
numbers. This alpha is sort of your basic&nbsp;
variable. So alpha was just a name for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:31.380
multi-set consisting of a single one. I want to&nbsp;
change the name of that now, okay? And this is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:37.080
you know, seemingly unmotivated until we go to&nbsp;
the multi point of view and then you see, ah,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:41.400
there's actually a very good reason for doing&nbsp;
this. Okay, so we're going to change the name&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:48.480
from alpha to alpha 0 or alpha sub 0. Okay, so&nbsp;
we're going to make that change. So now the name&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:55.980
of this mset, the mset consisting just of one, is&nbsp;
now going to be alpha 0, alpha sub 0. Okay, so let&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:55.980 --> 00:12:00.480
me remind you, there's some basic facts about this&nbsp;
thing. So if you take two alpha 0, in other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:07.920
alpha 0 plus alpha 0, that's mset 1 plus mset 1.&nbsp;
Dump them together, you get mset 1, 1. Similarly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:14.820
three alpha 0 will be mset 1, 1, 1. If we&nbsp;
multiply this thing by itself, alpha 0 squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:22.920
we have mset 1 times mset 1. We perform that by&nbsp;
adding the ingredients 1 plus 1 in there, so we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.920 --> 00:12:31.800
get mset 2. And similarly, alpha 0 cubed is mset&nbsp;
3 and so on. So now when we have a general poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.800 --> 00:12:40.320
number like this thing here, mset 0, 0, 0, 1, 3,&nbsp;
4, 4, we can write that as a more usual polynomial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:48.180
in alpha 0 here. Okay, by first of all sort of&nbsp;
decomposing this into its various types. So 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:48.180 --> 00:12:54.480
0, 0 is 1 mset, mset 1, mset 3, mset 4, 4, and&nbsp;
then we recognize this thing here is just the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.480 --> 00:13:01.500
number 3. This is what we're calling alpha 0. This&nbsp;
thing here, this single 3, that was alpha 0 cubed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:07.800
A single 4 would be alpha 0 to the fourth, and&nbsp;
there's two of them here. So in the same way here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:17.280
we get 2 alpha 0 to the fourth. Okay, so this&nbsp;
works better now because when we go to multi,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:25.380
what we want to do is introduce a new object,&nbsp;
which is the previous object, namely alpha 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:33.060
put into an mset. Okay, so we're going to take the&nbsp;
mset now consisting of alpha 0, and we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:33.060 --> 00:13:42.480
give that a new name. That's going to be alpha sub&nbsp;
1. Okay, so alpha sub 1 is alpha sub 0 in an mset.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:49.740
And I have to emphasize the important distinction&nbsp;
throughout this story of having an object and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:55.680
having that object in an mset. Okay, those are&nbsp;
two different things, and sometimes they're quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:55.680 --> 00:14:03.780
different things. Okay, so you have to keep that&nbsp;
separation in mind. Alpha 0 is this thing. Alpha&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:03.780 --> 00:14:08.340
1 is the alpha 0 in the mset. And actually,&nbsp;
you know, if we wrote it out just in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:14.400
brackets, it would look like this. So alpha 1 is&nbsp;
the mset consisting of alpha 0. There's alpha 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:23.820
mset 1. And what is 1? Well, 1 is actually mset 0.&nbsp;
Okay, and what is 0 actually? Well, 0 is the empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.820 --> 00:14:30.420
mset. So we could sort of parse this by seeing&nbsp;
that this alpha 1 is really, you know, a pair of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:34.800
brackets containing a pair of brackets containing&nbsp;
a pair of brackets containing a pair of brackets.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:46.560
Ultimately, it's just brackets. That's alpha sub&nbsp;
1. That's now our basic multi number which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:54.060
not itself a poly number. It's the starting point&nbsp;
from going from the poly world to the multi-world.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.780 --> 00:15:00.120
Okay, so let's do some basic arithmetic now&nbsp;
with multi numbers using this new notation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:07.740
and we'll sort of see how it works. And it&nbsp;
also suggests that there's something else&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:15.960
that we need to introduce. Okay, so alpha sub 1,&nbsp;
that's mset alpha 0. Okay, so two alpha sub 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.960 --> 00:15:21.180
or I'll just say two alpha 1, is what you get&nbsp;
when you take two of these guys and dump them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.180 --> 00:15:29.160
together. So it's mset alpha 0, alpha 0, which&nbsp;
in terms of numbers is mset, mset 1, mset 1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:39.000
There's an alpha 0. There's another alpha 0.&nbsp;
Three alpha 1 will be mset consisting of mset 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.640
mset 1, mset 1. That's an alpha 0,&nbsp;
that's an alpha 0, that's an alpha 0.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:51.120
How about alpha 1 squared? Okay, so we're&nbsp;
squaring, multiplying this thing by itself.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:51.780 --> 00:15:57.120
Well, the way you multiply msets&nbsp;
is you form another mset whose&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.900 --> 00:16:03.540
entries are the possible sums of entries here&nbsp;
and here. Well, there's only one entry here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.540 --> 00:16:07.680
and one entry here, one element here, one element&nbsp;
here, so there's only one possible sum that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:15.720
going to form: alpha 0 plus alpha 0. Alpha&nbsp;
0 is mset 1, so we have mset 1 plus mset 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:15.720 --> 00:16:22.620
and that is mset 1, 1, right? We're just&nbsp;
dumping these two ones out into a separate box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:22.620 --> 00:16:28.860
so we get another box with the two ones in&nbsp;
it. Okay, so that's what alpha sub 1 squared&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:36.720
looks like. Similarly, alpha 1 cubed looks like&nbsp;
this: it's an mset consisting of mset 1, 1, 1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.340 --> 00:16:47.700
So here is a poly number in alpha 1, okay? Say 3&nbsp;
plus alpha 1 plus 4 alpha 1 squared plus alpha 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.700 --> 00:16:56.640
to the fifth. We wanted to write that out. The&nbsp;
3 is mset 0, 0, 0. The alpha 1, well, that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.420 --> 00:17:04.260
the same thing we've been talking about: mset,&nbsp;
mset 1. It's an mset containing just alpha 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:12.060
and alpha 1 squared, that was this thing here,&nbsp;
and we have four of them, so we have four of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:18.900
